      "rawMarkdown": "# 31. Adulterate\n\n**Pronunciation:** uh-DUL-tuh-rayt\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To make something impure or worse by adding something bad or inferior.\n**Bangla meaning:** ভেজাল মেশানো, বিশুদ্ধতা নষ্ট করা, নিম্নমানের করা\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *adulterare*, meaning “to corrupt, pollute, or falsify.” The original idea is making something less pure than it was.\n\n**Simple explanation:** If someone adulterates milk, oil, medicine, food, or data, they mix in something bad or false, so the original thing loses quality.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Adulterate = add dirt / add lower-quality material.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** contaminate, debase, corrupt, taint, pollute, dilute\n**Basic synonyms:** mix badly, make impure, spoil, lower quality\n**Antonyms:** purify, refine, cleanse, improve\n**Common usage:** adulterated food, adulterated milk, adulterated data, adulterated evidence\n**Confusing word:** **Adulterate ≠ Adultery.** Adulterate = ভেজাল মেশানো; adultery = marital unfaithfulness.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The seller adulterated the milk with water.\n2. Cheap oil can adulterate good-quality fuel.\n3. The company was fined for selling adulterated spices.\n4. The researcher warned that biased sampling could adulterate the results.\n5. If the evidence is adulterated, the court cannot trust it.\n6. The drug lost effectiveness after being adulterated with inactive chemicals.\n7. A single false entry can adulterate an entire database.\n8. In public health studies, adulterated medicine is a serious threat to patient safety.\n9. In food-quality research, laboratories test whether imported honey has been adulterated with sugar syrup.\n10. The integrity of the experiment was compromised because the sample had been adulterated before analysis.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The river was **contaminated** by industrial waste.\n2. False data can **contaminate** a scientific model.\n3. The dictator’s greed **debased** public institutions.\n4. Plagiarism can **debase** an academic paper.\n5. The official tried to **corrupt** the investigation.\n6. Rumors can **taint** a person’s reputation.\n7. The scandal **tainted** the minister’s career.\n8. Factories may **pollute** groundwater with untreated waste.\n9. Propaganda can **pollute** public debate.\n10. Adding weak evidence may **dilute** a strong argument.\n11. Overuse of clichés can **dilute** the force of an essay.\n12. Fraudulent reports **corrupted** the company’s financial record.\n13. Biased assumptions **contaminated** the policy analysis.\n14. The cheap filler **debased** the original product.\n15. Poor translation can **taint** the meaning of a legal document.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Adulterate = make impure by adding bad material = ভেজাল মেশানো**\n\n---",
