      "rawMarkdown": "# 44. Calumny\n\n**Pronunciation:** KAL-əm-nee\n**Part of speech:** Noun\n**Core meaning:** A false statement made to damage someone’s reputation.\n**Bangla meaning:** অপবাদ, মানহানিকর মিথ্যা অভিযোগ, কুৎসা\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *calumnia*, meaning false accusation or trickery. It carries the idea of malicious lying.\n\n**Simple explanation:** Calumny is not just criticism. It is a false and damaging accusation.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Calumny = calculated lie against someone.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** slander, defamation, libel, vilification, smear\n**Basic synonyms:** false accusation, reputation attack, lie, character attack\n**Antonyms:** praise, vindication, defense, compliment\n**Common usage:** spread calumny, political calumny, victim of calumny, vile calumny\n**Confusing word:** **Calumny ≠ Column.** Calumny = অপবাদ; column = newspaper/building column.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The accusation was pure calumny.\n2. He suffered because of calumny.\n3. The newspaper printed calumny about the teacher.\n4. The candidate denied the calumny spread by his opponents.\n5. Calumny can destroy a person’s reputation.\n6. The court punished the writer for malicious calumny.\n7. The article was not fair criticism; it was calumny.\n8. In political campaigns, calumny often spreads faster than verified information.\n9. In academic communities, calumny against a researcher can damage trust and careers.\n10. The historian argued that the leader’s reputation had been shaped less by evidence than by decades of partisan calumny.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The actor sued the magazine for **slander**.\n2. Repeated **slander** ruined his reputation.\n3. The company filed a case for **defamation**.\n4. Public **defamation** can have severe legal consequences.\n5. The article was considered **libel** because it printed false claims.\n6. Online **libel** can spread quickly.\n7. The speech became a campaign of **vilification**.\n8. The activist faced constant **vilification** from opponents.\n9. The rumor was a deliberate **smear**.\n10. The politician called the accusation a **smear campaign**.\n11. The false story was a **character attack**.\n12. The report rejected the **malicious charge** as unsupported.\n13. The witness exposed the **false accusation**.\n14. The journalist avoided **defamatory** language.\n15. The court ruled that the pamphlet was not criticism but **calumny**, designed to damage the candidate’s name.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Calumny = damaging false accusation = অপবাদ**\n\n---",
