      "rawMarkdown": "# 45. Candid\n\n**Pronunciation:** KAN-did\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Honest, direct, and open in speech.\n**Bangla meaning:** অকপট, সরাসরি, স্পষ্টবাদী, খোলামেলা\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *candidus*, meaning “white, bright, pure.” The idea moved from physical brightness to moral openness and honesty.\n\n**Simple explanation:** A candid person speaks honestly without hiding the truth, but not necessarily rudely.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Candid = clean and clear truth.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** frank, forthright, outspoken, sincere, straightforward\n**Basic synonyms:** honest, open, direct, truthful\n**Antonyms:** evasive, deceptive, dishonest, insincere\n**Common usage:** candid interview, candid opinion, candid response, candid discussion\n**Confusing word:** **Candid ≠ Candidate.** Candid = honest/direct; candidate = applicant or nominee.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. She gave a candid answer.\n2. I need your candid opinion.\n3. His candid reply surprised everyone.\n4. The manager was candid about the company’s problems.\n5. The doctor gave a candid explanation of the risks.\n6. The report offered a candid assessment of the project’s failures.\n7. The professor appreciated the student’s candid feedback.\n8. In peer review, candid criticism helps authors improve weak arguments.\n9. In engineering safety reports, candid disclosure of design flaws can prevent accidents.\n10. The committee’s candid evaluation revealed that the policy was popular but poorly implemented.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. She gave a **frank** explanation of the mistake.\n2. The minister’s **frank** admission surprised reporters.\n3. His **forthright** answer left no room for doubt.\n4. A **forthright** leader admits failure.\n5. The professor was **outspoken** about academic dishonesty.\n6. The critic remained **outspoken** despite pressure.\n7. Her apology sounded **sincere**.\n8. The witness gave a **sincere** statement.\n9. The report was **straightforward** and easy to understand.\n10. A **straightforward** answer is better than a vague excuse.\n11. The researcher was **honest** about the limitations.\n12. The discussion was **open** and productive.\n13. The employee gave a **truthful** account of the accident.\n14. The review was **direct** but constructive.\n15. The committee praised the author’s **candid** acknowledgment that the study’s sample size was limited.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Candid = honest and direct = অকপট**\n\n---\n\n## Compact Summary Table — Words 31–45\n\n| No. | Word          | Core meaning              | Bangla        | Strong synonyms              | Opposite   |\n| --: | ------------- | ------------------------- | ------------- | ---------------------------- | ---------- |\n|  31 | Adulterate    | make impure               | ভেজাল মেশানো  | contaminate, debase, corrupt | purify     |\n|  32 | Advocate      | support publicly          | সমর্থন করা    | champion, endorse, espouse   | oppose     |\n|  33 | Aggrandize    | increase power/status     | বড় করে তোলা   | enlarge, magnify, elevate    | diminish   |\n|  34 | Alacrity      | eager quickness           | সানন্দ তৎপরতা | eagerness, promptness        | reluctance |\n|  35 | Ambivalent    | mixed feelings            | দ্বিধাগ্রস্ত  | conflicted, equivocal        | certain    |\n|  36 | Ameliorate    | make better               | উন্নতি করা    | improve, alleviate, mitigate | worsen     |\n|  37 | Amenable      | willing to cooperate      | রাজি, অনুকূল  | receptive, compliant         | stubborn   |\n|  38 | Anachronistic | outdated/wrong time       | কালবিরোধী     | archaic, obsolete            | modern     |\n|  39 | Audacious     | boldly daring             | দুঃসাহসী      | bold, daring, intrepid       | timid      |\n|  40 | Avaricious    | extremely greedy          | অতিলোভী       | greedy, rapacious            | generous   |\n|  41 | Banal         | boringly common           | গতানুগতিক     | trite, hackneyed             | original   |\n|  42 | Benign        | harmless/kind             | নিরীহ, সদয়    | harmless, gentle             | malignant  |\n|  43 | Brazen        | shamelessly bold          | নির্লজ্জ      | impudent, blatant            | modest     |\n|  44 | Calumny       | damaging false accusation | অপবাদ         | slander, defamation          | praise     |\n|  45 | Candid        | honest/direct             | অকপট          | frank, forthright            | deceptive  |\n\n---\n\n## Quick Revision Section\n\nRevise these in 3 rounds:\n\n**Round 1 — Meaning:**\nRead only the word + Bangla + final memory line.\n\n**Round 2 — Synonym chain:**\nSay 2 GRE synonyms aloud.\nExample: **Banal = trite + hackneyed.**\n\n**Round 3 — GRE usage:**\nMake one serious sentence for each word.\nExample: *The committee offered a candid assessment of the policy’s weaknesses.*\n\n---\n## Day 2 GRE Vocabulary — Part 2\n\n### Words 46–60\n\nThe uploaded vocabulary lesson file lists Words 46–60 as: **Castigate, Caustic, Construe, Contrite, Convoluted, Covet, Craven, Decorum, Deft, Demur, Derivative, Desiccate, Diatribe, Incredulous, Ingenuous**. \n\n---",
