      "rawMarkdown": "# 47. Caustic\n\n**Pronunciation:** KAW-stik\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Chemically burning; or sharply sarcastic and hurtful.\n**Bangla meaning:** দাহক, ক্ষারক; তীক্ষ্ণ, কটাক্ষপূর্ণ, ব্যঙ্গাত্মক\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Greek *kaustikos*, meaning “capable of burning.” Later it also came to mean words that “burn” emotionally.\n\n**Simple explanation:** Caustic can describe a chemical that burns skin or a comment that hurts like acid.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Caustic comment = words that burn.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** corrosive, biting, sarcastic, scathing, acrid\n**Basic synonyms:** harsh, sharp, cutting, bitter\n**Antonyms:** gentle, kind, mild, soothing\n**Common usage:** caustic remark, caustic criticism, caustic chemical, caustic wit\n**Confusing word:** **Caustic ≠ Cautious.** Caustic = harsh/burning; cautious = careful.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The chemical was caustic and dangerous.\n2. His caustic joke hurt her feelings.\n3. The critic wrote a caustic review of the film.\n4. Her caustic tone made the apology sound insincere.\n5. The professor’s caustic comments discouraged the students.\n6. The report used caustic language to describe the policy failure.\n7. The politician’s caustic attack damaged the debate’s seriousness.\n8. In laboratory safety, caustic substances must be handled with protective equipment.\n9. In political analysis, caustic rhetoric can deepen public division.\n10. The article’s caustic assessment of the project was harsh but supported by evidence.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The acid was **corrosive** enough to damage metal.\n2. His **corrosive** cynicism weakened team morale.\n3. The columnist made a **biting** remark about the mayor.\n4. Her **biting** criticism exposed the plan’s flaws.\n5. The student gave a **sarcastic** answer to the teacher.\n6. The review was **sarcastic** rather than constructive.\n7. The report offered a **scathing** critique of the agency.\n8. The judge delivered a **scathing** rebuke.\n9. His **acrid** tone made the discussion unpleasant.\n10. The debate became **bitter** after personal attacks.\n11. The comedian’s **cutting** humor offended the audience.\n12. The editorial used **sharp** language to condemn corruption.\n13. The reviewer’s **harsh** comments were difficult to ignore.\n14. Her **acidic** wit made even friends uncomfortable.\n15. The scientist avoided **caustic** language, even while rejecting the flawed theory.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Caustic = burning chemically or verbally = দাহক / তীক্ষ্ণ ব্যঙ্গাত্মক**\n\n---",
