      "rawMarkdown": "# 48. Construe\n\n**Pronunciation:** kun-STROO\n**Part of speech:** Verb\n**Core meaning:** To interpret or understand something in a particular way.\n**Bangla meaning:** ব্যাখ্যা করা, অর্থ বোঝা, নির্দিষ্টভাবে গ্রহণ করা\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *construere*, meaning “to build together.” Meaning is “built” from words, evidence, or context.\n\n**Simple explanation:** To construe means to explain what something means, especially a statement, law, action, or evidence.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Construe = construct meaning.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** interpret, understand, read, infer, explain\n**Basic synonyms:** take, see, make sense of, define\n**Antonyms:** misinterpret, misunderstand, confuse, distort\n**Common usage:** construe a statement, construe a law, construe silence as agreement, construe evidence\n**Confusing word:** **Construe ≠ Construct.** Construct = build; construe = interpret meaning.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. Do not construe my silence as agreement.\n2. The lawyer construed the contract differently.\n3. His joke was construed as an insult.\n4. The public construed the delay as incompetence.\n5. The professor asked students to construe the poem carefully.\n6. The court construed the law in favor of the defendant.\n7. The data can be construed in more than one way.\n8. In legal research, judges may construe ambiguous language according to legislative intent.\n9. In social science, survey responses must be construed cautiously because wording can shape answers.\n10. The committee construed the minister’s vague statement as an attempt to avoid responsibility.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The judge **interpreted** the law narrowly.\n2. Historians **interpret** events through available evidence.\n3. She **understood** his silence as disapproval.\n4. The researcher **understood** the result as preliminary, not final.\n5. Many readers **read** the ending as ironic.\n6. The committee **read** the delay as a sign of internal conflict.\n7. From the evidence, scientists **inferred** a causal relationship.\n8. The analyst **inferred** weakness from the company’s declining revenue.\n9. The professor **explained** the passage line by line.\n10. The report **clarified** how the policy should be applied.\n11. The court **defined** the term more broadly than expected.\n12. Critics **viewed** the speech as evasive.\n13. Investors **took** the announcement as a warning.\n14. The evidence was **understood** to support the hypothesis.\n15. The phrase was **interpreted** differently by legal scholars and policymakers.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Construe = interpret meaning = ব্যাখ্যা করা**\n\n---",
