      "rawMarkdown": "# 55. Demur\n\n**Pronunciation:** dih-MUR\n**Part of speech:** Verb / Noun\n**Core meaning:** To object politely or hesitate because of doubt.\n**Bangla meaning:** আপত্তি করা, দ্বিধা করা, ভদ্রভাবে অসম্মতি জানানো\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *demorari*, meaning “to delay.” The idea: you pause or object before accepting something.\n\n**Simple explanation:** To demur means to disagree, object, or hesitate, usually politely.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Demur = delay with an objection.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** object, protest, dissent, hesitate, balk\n**Basic synonyms:** disagree, refuse, question, resist\n**Antonyms:** agree, accept, consent, approve\n**Common usage:** demur at a proposal, demur politely, without demur, demur to a demand\n**Confusing word:** **Demur ≠ Demure.** Demur = object; demure = shy/modest.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. She demurred at the suggestion.\n2. He accepted the plan without demur.\n3. The lawyer demurred to the judge’s interpretation.\n4. The scientist demurred when asked to make an unsupported claim.\n5. The committee demurred at the high cost of the project.\n6. Investors demurred because the proposal lacked clear risk analysis.\n7. The student demurred politely, arguing that the evidence was incomplete.\n8. In academic debate, scholars may demur not to reject a theory entirely, but to question its assumptions.\n9. In engineering review, experts demurred at approving a design without stress testing.\n10. The board demurred because the plan promised growth but ignored environmental liabilities.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The lawyer **objected** to the evidence.\n2. Several scientists **objected** to the weak methodology.\n3. Citizens **protested** the unfair tax.\n4. The workers **protested** unsafe conditions.\n5. The judge allowed the minority to **dissent**.\n6. The professor **dissented** from the dominant interpretation.\n7. She **hesitated** before signing the contract.\n8. Investors **hesitated** because the risks were unclear.\n9. The horse **balked** at crossing the bridge.\n10. The committee **balked** at the enormous cost.\n11. The student **questioned** the assumption.\n12. The board **resisted** the change.\n13. The official **refused** to approve the document.\n14. The reviewer **took issue with** the paper’s conclusion.\n15. The panel **demurred** when asked to endorse a policy without supporting data.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Demur = politely object or hesitate = আপত্তি করা / দ্বিধা করা**\n\n---",
