      "rawMarkdown": "# 56. Derivative\n\n**Pronunciation:** dih-RIV-uh-tiv\n**Part of speech:** Adjective / Noun\n**Core meaning:** Not original; copied or developed from something else.\n**Bangla meaning:** অনুকরণমূলক, মৌলিক নয়, অন্য কিছু থেকে উদ্ভূত\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *derivare*, meaning “to draw off from a source.” Something derivative comes from another source.\n\n**Simple explanation:** A derivative idea, story, design, or argument depends too much on earlier work and lacks originality.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Derivative = derived from another source.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** imitative, unoriginal, copied, secondary, borrowed\n**Basic synonyms:** not new, based on, repeated, reproduced\n**Antonyms:** original, innovative, novel, creative\n**Common usage:** derivative work, derivative plot, derivative argument, derivative design\n**Confusing word:** **Derivative ≠ Derivation only in math.** In GRE, derivative often means unoriginal.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. The song sounded derivative.\n2. The movie had a derivative plot.\n3. His essay was accurate but derivative.\n4. The critic dismissed the novel as derivative.\n5. The design was derivative of older models.\n6. The theory was derivative rather than innovative.\n7. The student’s project was too derivative to receive high marks.\n8. In academic writing, derivative arguments add little to existing scholarship.\n9. In technology markets, derivative products often fail unless they improve on the original.\n10. The research proposal was criticized as derivative because it repeated earlier studies without a new question.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The painting was **imitative** of Renaissance masters.\n2. The essay felt **imitative** rather than independent.\n3. The story was **unoriginal** and predictable.\n4. The proposal was **unoriginal** despite its polished language.\n5. The design was clearly **copied** from a competitor.\n6. The student submitted a **copied** assignment.\n7. The argument was **secondary**, relying on others’ claims.\n8. The article offered only a **secondary** analysis.\n9. The melody sounded **borrowed** from an older song.\n10. His ideas were **borrowed** rather than developed.\n11. The film was **formulaic** in structure.\n12. The speech was **recycled** from earlier campaigns.\n13. The model was **adapted** from previous research.\n14. The book seemed **repetitive** because it offered no new insight.\n15. The reviewer called the paper **derivative**, noting that it merely restated established theories.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Derivative = not original; taken from another source = অনুকরণমূলক**\n\n---",
