      "rawMarkdown": "# 58. Diatribe\n\n**Pronunciation:** DYE-uh-tryb\n**Part of speech:** Noun\n**Core meaning:** A bitter, angry, and long verbal attack.\n**Bangla meaning:** তীব্র নিন্দা, আক্রমণাত্মক বক্তৃতা, কড়া সমালোচনামূলক বক্তব্য\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Greek roots originally meaning “discourse” or “spending time.” Later it came to mean a harsh critical speech.\n\n**Simple explanation:** A diatribe is not calm criticism. It is an angry, bitter, extended attack.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Diatribe = angry verbal attack.**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** tirade, rant, harangue, denunciation, invective\n**Basic synonyms:** angry speech, attack, bitter criticism, verbal assault\n**Antonyms:** praise, compliment, tribute, approval\n**Common usage:** political diatribe, angry diatribe, launch into a diatribe, diatribe against corruption\n**Confusing word:** **Diatribe ≠ Dialogue.** Diatribe = one-sided attack; dialogue = conversation.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. He launched into a diatribe against taxes.\n2. The speech became a bitter diatribe.\n3. Her complaint turned into a diatribe against management.\n4. The critic’s review was more diatribe than analysis.\n5. The politician delivered a diatribe against his opponents.\n6. The professor warned students not to replace argument with diatribe.\n7. The article was rejected because it read like a personal diatribe.\n8. In public debate, diatribes often generate attention but rarely solve problems.\n9. In academic writing, a diatribe weakens credibility because it replaces evidence with anger.\n10. The editorial began as a policy critique but became a diatribe full of accusations and sarcasm.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The coach’s speech became a **tirade** after the loss.\n2. The article was a **tirade** against corruption.\n3. He went on a long **rant** about the government.\n4. The meeting collapsed into a **rant** against management.\n5. The speaker delivered a harsh **harangue**.\n6. The crowd grew tired of the politician’s **harangue**.\n7. The committee issued a formal **denunciation** of the policy.\n8. The activist’s **denunciation** was forceful but evidence-based.\n9. The essay was filled with **invective**.\n10. The debate became personal **invective** rather than reasoning.\n11. The columnist wrote a bitter **attack** on the law.\n12. The speech was a **verbal assault** on the opposition.\n13. The review became **scathing criticism**.\n14. The minister’s address sounded like an angry **condemnation**.\n15. The researcher avoided **diatribe**, choosing instead to present data calmly.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Diatribe = bitter verbal attack = তীব্র নিন্দা**\n\n---",
