      "rawMarkdown": "# 59. Incredulous\n\n**Pronunciation:** in-KREJ-uh-ləs\n**Part of speech:** Adjective\n**Core meaning:** Unable or unwilling to believe something.\n**Bangla meaning:** অবিশ্বাসী, সন্দেহপ্রবণ, বিশ্বাস করতে না পারা\n\n**Root story / etymology:** From Latin *in-* = not + *credere* = believe. Incredulous literally means “not believing.”\n\n**Simple explanation:** If you are incredulous, you react with disbelief because something sounds unlikely or surprising.\n\n**Memory hook:** **Incredulous = “I cannot believe this.”**\n\n**GRE synonyms:** skeptical, disbelieving, doubtful, suspicious, unconvinced\n**Basic synonyms:** unbelieving, unsure, questioning, doubtful\n**Antonyms:** credulous, trusting, convinced, gullible\n**Common usage:** incredulous look, incredulous laugh, incredulous response, remain incredulous\n**Confusing word:** **Incredulous ≠ Incredible.** Incredulous = unbelieving person; incredible = unbelievable thing.\n\n### Examples — 10\n\n1. She gave him an incredulous look.\n2. He was incredulous when he heard the news.\n3. The audience remained incredulous after the magician’s trick.\n4. Scientists were incredulous about the claim until evidence appeared.\n5. Investors were incredulous when the company promised impossible returns.\n6. The professor was incredulous that no one had checked the data.\n7. The jury listened with incredulous silence.\n8. In peer review, scholars are often incredulous when a bold claim lacks evidence.\n9. In public health, experts were incredulous about a miracle cure advertised without clinical trials.\n10. The engineer was incredulous that the bridge design had been approved without load testing.\n\n### GRE synonym examples — 15\n\n1. The scientist was **skeptical** of the dramatic claim.\n2. Investors remained **skeptical** about the company’s forecast.\n3. The child looked **disbelieving** after hearing the story.\n4. The committee gave a **disbelieving** response.\n5. The judge was **doubtful** about the witness’s account.\n6. The researchers were **doubtful** of the early results.\n7. The officer became **suspicious** of the missing documents.\n8. The public was **suspicious** of the sudden policy change.\n9. The panel remained **unconvinced** by the explanation.\n10. The professor was **unconvinced** by the student’s excuse.\n11. The audience was **unbelieving** at first.\n12. The reviewer was **questioning** the paper’s assumptions.\n13. The doctor was **wary** of unsupported treatment claims.\n14. The analyst maintained a **critical** attitude toward the data.\n15. The board was **incredulous** that such a large error had escaped inspection.\n\n**Final memory line:** **Incredulous = not believing = অবিশ্বাসী**\n\n---",
